How does this network work?
Each transaction between two users actually takes place between two electronic addresses in the form of an e-mail.
Unless a user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information related to this transaction is electronically signed by a dual-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the file content, it is also possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist well in the public account book, broadcast throughout the network.
The key step is to write this new transaction in this book.
It is the resolution of a mathematical challenge to computers, and the winner of which, as a temporary central banker, will have the privilege of adding this additional line.
This is a file hacking phase, i.e. transformation of a large file into a shorter and more unique fingerprint.
Computers "take" the new transaction and add a number before they "find" the whole.
The aim is to find the number that gives a particular footprint (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, the other knots easily check that it's the right one.
The transaction is then indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any changes would change the print.
If, to fraud, a user wanted to pay twice with the same money very quickly (less than ten minutes), only one of the two transactions would be validated by the network - the other remaining orphan as both have different fingerprints.
The computer that solved the challenge wins 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided by two regularly, probably before the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but they are divisible up to 100 millionth, leaving the margin...
The challenge is also reflected in each increase in the calculation power.
