For the President, it is also a way of regaining popular and democratic legitimacy while the dispute rages throughout the country.
Mohammed Morsi seems to be convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favour, as he said in an interview with the American weekly Time.
The use of such a precipitous vote is a matter of the ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "You vote for my text, or I keep the full powers," which they are supposed to end after the adoption of the Constitution.
It is in a strange atmosphere that 85 members of this constituent Assembly, a large Islamic majority, voted on the text yesterday.
Most Liberals were missing the call.
