Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the Ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was admitted as the twentieth member of this agency, the second Member State of the former Eastern bloc (the Czech Republic became a full member on 12 November 2008).
Poland had begun close collaboration with ESA in 1994 and in the years that followed participated in a number of Agency projects.
However, the road from Poland to outer space started much earlier.
Already before the Second World War, passionate Poles were working on space flights; they did not always encounter understanding.
For example, I would like to refer to the conference of A. Šternfeld at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory on 6 December 1933, in which he presented ideas drawn from his cutting-edge work entitled "Introduction to Astronautics ".
The developments of this young engineer (born in 1905) left the cold listeners and years later Šternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld won the Robert Esnault-Pelterie Prize in France and André Louis Hirsch for his book "Introduction to Astronautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great propagator of astronomy and astronomy.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish newspapers and wrote many books devoted to this scientific discipline.
Gadomski has become a propagator of the world-renowned astronaut, in particular his contribution was rewarded by the fact that his name was given to one of the craters on the hidden side of the Moon.
From 1925 a drachma was built in Poland to be equipped with a rocketed engine.
Unfortunately, neither the author nor the details of this project are known.
Nor is it clear whether the rocket was to be used to propel or brake the drasin.
The only information known about this drama is the press of the time.
From 1933 onwards, the Polish artillery began to devote itself to the rockets.
The research was conducted by the Komorka Techniki Uzbrojenia Institute in collaboration with Professors Mieczyslaw Wolfke and Gustav Mokrzyckiego.
It appears from the retained documents that this research had reached the test stage.
Of course, with the arrival of the German armies, the research stopped.
In 1937, the plans of a photographic hunting rocket, drawn by engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the specialized press and the following year was published the book "Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakietobomba lotnicza" by an author named Leliwy-Krzywoblocki.
Both projects aimed at military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, all projects for the use of rocket technology were carried out by the interim scientific advisory committee ("Tymczasowy Advisory Committee Doradczo-Naukowy"), which coordinated all the work.
The committee had been established in 1937, but after two years of operation, the war ended its activities.
After the war, other works devoted to the aircraft were published in the Polish press, thanks to the Polish Astronautic Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
For the first time, there is a company in the November 1954 issue of the Problem newspaper, in which there are four more detailed articles on aeronautical.
In one of these articles, written by Professor Mr. Subotowicze, it is proposed to create an astronomical society
At that time, artificial satellite projects had already been launched and it was clear that space research had a future.
At the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautic Society (PTA) made efforts to enter the international Astronautic Federation (created in 1951) and in the fall, the PTA became a regular member.
The following year, the first PTA President, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became Vice-President of the International Astronautic Federation.
He kept his job until his death in 1959.
From 1956 onwards, the PTA made a significant contribution to the successful development of the RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) meteorological rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first model, RM-1, was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
This rocket with a range of 1800 meters had a length of 80 cm and weighed a little less than 5 kg.
Subsequently, an improved version was built, RM-1A, and during the summer of 1959, two-storey RM-2 flight tests were started in the Bledov Desert.
This rocket had a length of 1.4 meters and probably weighed 11.5 kg.
The following prototype should have been able to carry out concrete scientific work - the RM-34 rocket should have reached up to 14.5 km and served to observe the wind at altitude.
But in 1963, all development work was stopped.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed during the period 1962 - 1965, followed by the first RM rockets.
This rocket, designed with two floors, had a total length of 510 cm and an initial weight of 32.5 kg.
Three models (called Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed; they were distinguished by the dimensions of space reserved for scientific tools.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 liters, while in Meteor-1B this volume was 0.34 liters and in Meteor-1C 0.62 liters.
The maximum range of all these types of equipment was 37 km.
In the period 1965 - 1968, Meteor-2 rockets were developed in the aeronautical institute, the first flight tests began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had an initial weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a useful load of 10 kg at an altitude of approximately 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
The entry of Poland to the COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the establishment of a national COSPAR committee two years later should also be mentioned.
Under the Interkosmos programme, Poland also participated in the space exploration of artificial Soviet satellites and, in 1978, pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became, after Vladimir Remek, the second non-Soviet cosmonaut of this programme.
The repeal of the Public Use Act is not a solution.
Last week, the Constitutional Court repealed the law on public utility work.
This decision raised a lively discussion in public opinion.
It is certainly interesting to look at this issue from a broader perspective.
Economic systems oriented towards liberalism, both in the EU and in the context of globalization, are based on the principle of more unregulated economic competition.
This specifically means that the different economic entities and national economic systems are perpetually in conflict with each other.
This is the result of the principle of free trade and free movement (without limits) of private capital coupled with a fearful financial speculation.
The considerable differences in labour price (salaries) generate pressure on prices.
The following meaning must be stated: a producer strives to import low-selling goods which are resistant to economic competition by making the price of the competitor more expensive, with the aim of removing a larger share of the market and thereby increasing its own profits.
On a large scale, this means for most entrepreneurs: either to transfer production abroad, either to buy at low prices or to disappear. The result is significant unemployment in countries where labour prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and hence responsibility for the unemployment it generates, the social burdens of the State necessarily increase.
This situation intensifies the perfect will of the gentlemen of entrepreneurs to pay taxes and thus compensate for the economic and social damage caused to society as a whole by this race for profit.
This situation is so well known that it is not necessary to provide concrete statistical data.
Unscrupulous private capital practices create a situation in the various economies in which governments in different countries are forced to engage in mutual competition in order to artificially lower the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to them.
In other words, governments place their own people on the mercy of private capital without taking account of social collapse.
This is reflected mainly in the amendments to the laws in force.
The objective is to economically force its own population to accept the private capital price diktat, particularly in the area of wages.
This occurs on the one hand by a system of economic constraints in the event of long-term unemployment and on the other by restricting employees' rights in the field of labour legislation.
This results in increasing poverty and deepening the differences between the rich and the poor.
In the RFA, there have been public food distribution points for the poor for years that cannot meet their needs with their own work.
There are already millions of these people.
As part of the increase in the competitiveness of the German economy, it becomes quite common for employees to receive such wages that the state is obliged to pay an extra to achieve the minimum vital.
Such a scandal has, for example, been updated in the case of employees working as an assistant to the federal parliament.
The economic measures of almost all the Member States in the south of the EU undoubtedly generate a similar situation in which, under the pressure of a catastrophic collapse of society, people are forced either to emigrate (as in the 19th century) or to live with wages of misery, on the margins of society, in the hope that one day private capital will invest in their country.
