If it comes from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another; this capital may not come either, or then a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, a Turk, a Moroccan, an Egyptian or an African will continue to work for a fraction of a European wage.
This also concerns all Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media argue, to the point, that the state cannot make capital investments in its own economy, that the economy leads to an economic disaster.
Private capital strongly argues that the state cannot intervene in the economy through regulatory interventions.
We must ask ourselves, then, whether private capital does not influence and, even, does not govern today, according to its own selfish interests, politics and by the same, the whole state.
The answer to that question is certainly yes.
The evidence is that there is a nearly all-powerful lobby in all States.
This results in a desperate situation in the area of corruption, through the granting of mutual benefits, in legislation, where everything is condemned but not punishable.
In RFA, the situation is such that due to the lack of financial resources, national departments delegate the development of bills to firms of lawyers that are closely related to industry.
