The film Argo: When everything goes wrong, call Hollywood.
In November 1979, a number of protesters, including Islamist students, attacked the American Embassy of Tehran and held 52 diplomats hostages.
They were to be released in exchange for Shah, Mohammad Reza Pahlavi, who, after the revolution, had fled to the United States, which had supported his regime for several decades.
The situation did not offer the US administration a positive outcome, it could not, indeed, abandon Shah, because it would have seriously undermined the confidence of its allies in other countries.
However, in Iran, where the revolution had led to the establishment of a theocratic regime, it was unable to obtain the release of hostages.
It was a hard blow for the prestige of the United States, even worsened later by the fiasco of the attempt to release hostages by force.
The sequestrian diplomats were finally released 444 days later, following the negotiations organized by the Algerian government.
Their fate in the United States creates a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment.
The Iranian debacle greatly contributed to Jimmy Carter's defeat of Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential elections.
The film Argo, by the actor and director Ben Affleck, describes an episode of this story that offers a small victory to America.
Just before she was occupied, six employees escaped the embassy.
After complicated periods, they found themselves in the Ambassador of Canada's residence.
In collaboration with the Canadian authorities, the CIA managed to get them out of Iran with a rock cover: they left the country with Canadian passports as members of a shooting team to track down a large-scale science-fiction film.
Combination of genders
Tony Mendez's exfiltration expert plan requires Hollywood's collaboration.
In order to make the legend more credible, specialized stores reported this film project, press conferences were organized and a fictional production company had real offices.
The details of the operation were long kept secret, and the film was based on Tony Mendez's memories.
Affleck's film is an unusual combination of several genres.
It is a part of a political thriller designed in a realistic way but also a "caper movie", the story of a successful coup, a betrayal - for example, in the Ocean's high trilogy, twelve and thirteen.
The ambiances follow: sequences of documentary-style Tehran (in the sequences under title are presented iconic photographs of the time of events and how, thanks to these photos, these same situations have been rewritten in the film, there are no major differences),
Hollywood's lighter passages, treated with irony and a little exaggeration,
and then scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions with costumed men discussing the situation around conference tables, in corridors and on the phone...
Ben Affleck managed to reboot his career in a remarkable way.
As a ridiculous actor, he became a respected actor and his acting game stopped triggering ironic remarks.
Argo is his third long film after the dark police officer " Gone Baby Gone " (2007) and the thriller "The town" (2010).
It's also Affleck's first film that doesn't take place in his home town, Boston.
The sense of the atmosphere of a place is one of the characteristics that placed its first films above Hollywood standards.
Affleck also demonstrates this sense of atmosphere in Argo where the role of Tehran "is held" by Canada.
The best scenes of the film take place in streets, during the reconstruction of real facts; the initial sequence of the embassy fall is impressive by its clarity that also suggests confusion and unpredictability occurring when suddenly, in a given place, a history page is written.
Affleck and his collaborators have a similar effect in fictional scenes (the false shooting team in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many actions to too many places
The director had to be content with a subject offering only a few touching scenes, in the cinematographic sense of the term.
It goes well, it sometimes adds some elements to reality and there, the result is not always as elegant (the scene in which the threat of crisis at Tehran airport is removed by a phone call in America and the pursuit on the runway is quite drawn by the hair).
Argo's weakness lies in its dissipated nature, due to the need to show too many events to too many different places.
