Today, no one's doing his best in one of these regular libraries, right?
Spijkenisse, a sleeping town that has nothing attractive at the gates of Rotterdam, holds a rather special record.
The commune of 80,000 souls shows the lowest education rate in the Netherlands.
In order to restore some neurons to the brains, the city decided, a few years ago, to contribute to the general culture and reproduce the seven fictional bridges that appear on euro banknotes in the form of beautiful small miniature painted reinforced concrete.
The success of the cultural offensive remained limited.
This is how the city authorities have realized that there was only one way to get their hands on statistics: the construction of a library!
Winy Maas, from Rotterdam MVRDV's Architects' Office, master of audacious baton diagrams and creator of spirited and often cynical buildings, accepted the project with its usual flegme and presented himself to the competition in 2003 with five books under the arm and a squeezing on the face.
And while the members of the jury were still looking at themselves, bewildered and hoisting their shoulders, Maas, faced, stacked his books of choice in order of size to make a pyramid, and finished his speech backed up by activist arguments by one: "very common!"
Here it is, my proposal for the Spijkenisse Book Mountain, or as we say, the Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the 30 million euro mountain has landed.
The building is part of a revitalization project that also includes underground parking, supermarket, post office and a few buildings and houses for a total of 50 houses.
Early November, the Book Mountain received the second prize "Best Library of NL 2012".
In addition, the project was selected for the 2012 Dutch National Wood Award.
That is how this small terne village, which so far had nothing more to offer than a post-modern pedestrian area and a mayor of a juicy laideur, whose white facades invite to think that they sheltered a dairy, has enriched a contemporary architectural work.
The most important thing is that Spijkenisse now owns the first public cultural building in his history.
The Long Path to Reading
First impression: Eldorado of the book under cheese bell.
Of course, an elevator takes you to the heart of the massif, but the real joys of reading and architecture open up to you when you soak the floor of the building in the discovery of its topography.
The interior entirely made of glass is bright and clear, the ground in Dutch brick and the elegant reverberators speak unequivocally the language of the municipal public places.
The urban atmosphere is perfect.
We're already looking for public banks, dogs and small boys and girls playing at the ball.
And all books, books, and more books.
"Normally, library rays are located along the facade and in the middle there is a large and dark room, which is often uncomfortable and impersonal," says Willy Maas.
We have completely upset the classical spatial configuration and opened the reading spaces from the inside to the outside.
The interior of the mountain of books has been properly constructed: in the middle are the offices, the Internet library, the chess club, the center for the environment and the technical center of the building.
A special beauty lies in the black rays of the library, which are sometimes shaded, sometimes balustraded, sometimes climbing ramps.
A new experience for sight, touch and smell.
Even the architects and engineers of the hardy building don't want unknown materials.
"We wanted to work with recycled materials," says Joop Trouborst, project leader at the municipality of Spijkenisse, in a response to the Standard.
This is how one day we found an ad hoc waste from agriculture in an agricultural business.
In the Netherlands, for years the synthetic membrane of a millimetre thickness is used as a substrate in greenhouses and fields.
It's cheap and we're saving time.
The membrane finish is used for one or two seasons, then you can discard it.
For the library, the membrane was first compressed in such quantities in plates of a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the effect of heat and pressure, the "Landbouwplastic" (KPL) changes color and turns into a dark, homogeneous and resistant material, the smell of which evokes both a new car and sports shoes.
At the top of the 105 steps is the top of the mountain.
At the end of almost 500 metres, the literary café offers us an impressive view of the city, but also Dutch croquettes and pot ficus.
The latter create an atmosphere, but they contribute mainly to the maintenance of the ideal level of humidity of the literary mountain air.
Gifts for the New Soul
"It's amazing, but despite all the glass surfaces, this building is a model project in the field of ecology," Trouborst says.
The temperature of the building is controlled by geothermal.
Although the mountain of books is below a glass bell, the sun only illuminates the interior, even the days of beautiful weather.
The thick wooden beams mounted through the glass façade serves as a sunscreen, intercepting a large part of the rays.
The ambient atmosphere is very pleasant.
The fully automated stores are responsible for the rest.
Stefan Spermon, the septic scientist mentioned above, has already risked entering the new library.
Lisette Verhaig was already there, too.
Cynthia Bogarde, professor of traditional Chinese medicine, even describes Boekenberg as "the soul finally found" of Spijkenisse.
A few weeks ago, at the inauguration, each citizen was invited to donate a book from his personal library.
This measure has helped to fill the gaps in the library which was not yet completely garnished (now it has 70,000 books).
The concept is a success.
The rays overflow everywhere.
For architect Winy Maas, "there's nothing worse than a half-empty library."
"I believe our invitation has created a certain relationship between every citizen and this new building.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration."
In this way, MVRDV has achieved the master discipline that is called, in the professional jargon, "the creation of an identity".
Spijkenisse has written a new literary history page.
Even though she may appear young and uneducated.
This is finally a new starting point for the birth of an identity.
Szabo: "Germans must play a greater role."
Germany chose abstention in voting on the admission of the Palestinian State.
According to Stephen Szabo, an expert on relations between the United States and the EU, this decision puts Berlin in a delicate political situation.
Deutsche Welle: At the beginning of the week, Germany had announced its intention to vote against the Palestinian request for observer status with the United Nations.
But then she chose abstention.
Why?
Stephen Szabo: Germany does not approve of what the Israelis did in Gaza.
However, Berlin must be cautious, as it maintains special relations with Israel.
But I also think she doesn't support the American position either.
Germany wanted to affirm its independence, however, without being too critical to Israel.
At the insurrection in Libya in March 2011, Germany had also chosen to abstain in the vote on the establishment of an area of air exclusion.
Finally, NATO imposes this measure.
Is Germany having difficulty adopting a clear position on major international issues?
The answer is yes.
The reason is that Berlin is reviewing its foreign policy, seeking to move away from a policy so as to be defined by the Americans and to establish a German foreign policy.
Moreover, the lack of consistent and common policy within the Union complicates the situation.
The Germans therefore clash with several fronts.
They are expected to play a more independent role, but they are not used to it.
I think they are still trying to find that role, but they're on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
A foreign policy, such as France or Great Britain
What does the term "normal" foreign policy mean for the Germans?
It expresses the desire to adopt positions independent of those of the United States and European partners, including with regard to national dossiers.
I believe that German foreign policy is also determined by its economic policy, so by exports and relations with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Near East.
German economic interests are, to some extent, different from those of other major powers: that is why Germany must protect its interests.
Have these economic interests influenced Germany's position regarding the conflict in the Near East and abstention in the United Nations vote?
Germany first has important developments in the Near East, especially in the Gulf countries.
This is why Berlin must take care not to strike public opinion, but also the elites of the Arab countries.
This is undoubtedly a decisive element.
However, I would not attach too much importance to it, as it is not solely unilateral relations.
But this is, at any rate, a decisive element in German strategic thinking.
Does Germany undermine relations with the United States by choosing abstention in important votes, as in the case of Palestine?
I think that Europeans and Americans fully understand the German position.
That is why I think the fracture is not so serious that it was in the case of the Libyan question.
Perhaps even Germany will only be respected.
Germany thus demonstrated that it must be taken seriously as an international actor and that its interests must be taken into account.
In Europe, opinions on the Palestinian initiative are diverse.
On the other hand, the United States announced its veto with a clear voice.
Do the views differ between the United States and the majority of European countries?
There have always been differences because of the U.S. domestic political scene.
I believe that the Obama Administration is secretly showing great understanding of the European position.
But given the country's political configuration, of course, the government cannot publicly defend its position.
I believe that the real differences of opinion are not so great that they always seem so.
If you observe the relations between Obama and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahou, you will notice that Obama is far from engulfing enthusiasm for Netanyahou's policy.
Does Germany experience difficulties in reconciling its close relations with Israel and the United States, on the one hand, with the position of the major European partners on the other?
I don't think it's easy for the Germans.
Of course, it would be a little simpler for the Germans if there was a coherent and uniform European policy, but today that is not the case.
They cannot therefore enter a broader political line and must affirm their unique position.
This is what they are currently doing in the issue of the euro.
In my opinion, Germany will play a locomotive role in the future and will move Europe to adopt a European position.
It is not simple for Germany, especially because of relations with Israel.
This question has always been delicate.
But in my opinion, the Germans are well aware that they have to play a role that makes them more independent.
Is Germany playing a role as a major player on the international stage, and does Germany only want to play a key role?
Or is it still difficult to assume leadership roles?
Germany is still not used to it, it is always uncomfortable and, for obvious reasons, the country still finds it difficult to play a more important role.
Looking at, for example, the crisis of the euro, it is noted that every time Germany decides to weigh more, many anti-German feelings are heard.
It doesn't make it easy for the Germans.
In fact, it is still the same problem: we do not want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more delicate position than the United States.
It must be composed of very varied neighbours and opinions, and it is not easy.
Today, the influence of the United States on European policy is only decreasing, but at the moment the EU is not filling this gap, while who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a more important role.
And even if they don't like it, even if it's unpleasant to them and if they're less appreciated, it's life!
Stephen Szabo is the Deputy Director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, an institute in which academics and political experts from Europe and North America jointly analyse the challenges of the transatlantic community.
Szabo is also a member of the German Marshall Fund, where he specialized in German politics, American foreign policy and transatlantic relations.
"Market Protection" in China: when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani and Polo Ralph Lauren are well known brands all over the world.
Armani Polo... what is this really about?
Behind this name is a trademark officially registered in China, but which has nothing to do with the original company.
The trade mark thus enjoys such protection that no complaint can be made by the company bearing the name.
And even if she could, it's not certain that she would gain cause.
"It is increasingly difficult for foreigners to protect their brands in China," says Thomas Pattloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing's firm specializing in violating property rights in the Far East.
Every week, a new file arrives on my desk.
Imitators need only a few extra letters in order to record their trademarks.
