The world's hardest profession: the human mules of Kawah Ijen
For four euros, the carriers of the Indonesian volcano risk their life and health by bringing 70 kilos of sulphur through the steep stone trails.
There are people for whom work is a hell and others who work literally in hell.
This is the case of Anto Wijaya, one of the 400 miners who earn their lives by bringing the sulphur of the Kawah Ijen volcano, east of the Indonesian island of Java.
He must work every day to the bottom of the crater, where the sulphur gas emanating from the earth's guts solidifies to the contact of the air.
After harvesting large sulphur rocks, which weigh about 70 pounds [70 kg], he installs them in two bamboo baskets that he loads on his shoulders through the steeped trails.
There are only 250 meters up to the top of the volcano that reaches 2,386 meters of altitude, but exhausted carriers take more than 40 minutes to scale this distance, at a tortoise allure, by keeping the balance and measuring their steps so as not to stumble and fall into the precipice.
They know that a false step could cost them their life, as it happened to a French tourist who made a deadly fall in the Kawah Ijen volcano several years ago.
The minors of Kawah Ijen earn 5 cents of euro for each kilo of sulphur extracted.
Once on the top, he wanders a path among tourists who photographed them as if they were circus animals, and carrying the heavy baskets painfully, they walk the 3 kilometers up to the balance that a mining company has set a little down at 1,850 meters altitude.
It is PT Candi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating the volcano since 1960 and, it can be said, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian rupees (5 cents of euro) per kilo of sulphur.
It then sells it at 10,000 rupees (83 cents euros) to the petrochemical industry because this mineral is very present in everyday life and is used to make candles, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
"As we carry about 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) on each trip," explains Anto, who generally travels three trips a day.
Everyone takes 3 hours and ends up exhausted, but this allows him to win $138,000 (11,50 euros) at the end of the day.
Although it seems to be a misery for such an overhuman effort, it is the triple of what he would gain in the fields.
"The income of minors is very high here, where the coffee harvest is paid 15,000 rupees (EUR 1,20) per day and where the average monthly wage is two million rupees (EUR 167)", says the carrier who used to work as a brick on the tourist island of Bali.
There, his salary was 75,000 rupees (€6.20) per day and the job was not so difficult, but then he returned to his family in Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a reason that, in Indonesia, is as indisputable as the sulphur: "I married a girl from Bali, where they are Hindus, and I brought her back to Java for conversion to Islam".
Then he suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughs constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases.
At 27 years of age, he spent three of his life challenging the danger on the Kawah ljen, but the sulphur has already started making him pay the bill although he covers his face with a mask and wears special gloves.
Then he suffers from asthma, breathes with difficulty, coughing constantly and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases rejected by the volcano.
