The Unasur Summit ended without the Lima Declaration being made public
The VIth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) was concluded today in Peru without the publication of the Lima Declaration, although it was previously announced and theoretically adopted by the seven representatives present.
Eff tried several times to access the document signed at the VIth Ordinary Meeting of Heads of State and Government of Unasur, but the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Presidency initially indicated that it would be disclosed after the conclusion of the summit and then stated that it would be published from time to time on the Peruvian government website.
When questioned on the text, they indicated that its content had been presented by the President of Peru, Ollante Humala, during brief press statements.
Journalists' access to information on the summit has been constantly limited.
During the day, only the soundless video of the presidential assembly with the message "private session, limited audio" was broadcast in the press room.
The limited information circulated among journalists was given by press officers from some of the Governments of Unasur who attended the meeting, with the exception of the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document released during the day was the list of presidents present, which caused some discomfort among hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who were demanding more important information.
Later, the presidency of Peru sent an e-mail to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it was President Humala's speech rather than the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru had been host to the 3rd Arab South America Summit (ASPA) and, on that occasion, although this was requested by the press, it had also not issued the declaration also called the Lima Declaration, as previously announced.
On the official website of ASPA, it can be verified that the document was published last March.
In both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities have tried to put in place safe transmission systems for all journalists, but they have limited information to the maximum.
The summit also concluded with the joint agreement of Chile and Peru to accept a judgment of the Hague Court which splits a different border between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, met at the regional meeting and declared that they would respect the ICJ's decision to hear the pleadings of both parties in the trial that Lima tried against Santiago and that began Monday in The Hague.
"We will respect and execute the verdict that will resolve the disputes that we are bringing before this international court today," said President Humala, next to his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has always been, and will continue to be a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of international disputes, treaties and tribunals," President Piñera added, handing a hand to President Humala, next to the flags of both countries.
The confirmation of the two presidents that they would submit to the ICJ took place after Colombia had this week denounced the Bogota Pact by which it had agreed to submit to the decisions of that international court, after a decision on the maritime limits with Nicaragua that it considered to be seriously wrong.
The summit was held without the presence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rouseff, Venezuela, Hugo Chávez, Bolivia, Evo Morales, and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, suspended from Unasur since 2011 after the removal of its former President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Ollanta Humala, was charged with opening the proceedings in the morning and closing the summit shortly after noon in Lima.
The representative read the final document in which he announced that 16 agreements had been adopted and that 31 project lines had been established between South American countries for a total of $17 million.
Among the agreements adopted, he mentioned that Unasur countries would set up "significant steps to achieve the goal of South American citizenship through the development of residence permit agreements".
He informed that actions would be put in place to improve "cooperation in combating urban insecurity and international organized crime, actions for improved accessibility to drugs, low-priced Internet access throughout South America, and to jointly and effectively assess the risks of natural disasters".
With a Europe in crisis, "economic consolidation (of Latin America) must not have a triumphal matrix but must help increase our productive matrix and provide a better future for our people," said President Humala.
"We have decided to favour a group of 31 iconic projects that improve the connection of South America's spaces, especially in rural and border areas... by uniting our countries and generating new economic circuits," said the Peruvian President in a speech.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five were concerned with Peru and were on the cross-cutting axes of its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and that two were aimed at a more important connection with Ecuador, although he did not give more details.
Similarly, the final document mentions the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the country's electoral process will allow its reintegration into the Union of South American Nations", of which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, integrated and having good relations with its neighbours, is another theme addressed at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos, stated, before starting the regional meeting, that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, the following Saturday in Mexico to discuss calmly the maritime dispute through a judgment of the ICJ requested by Bogota.
