Héctor "Hetin" Reyes "Basket-ball is my life"
"Hetin" Reyes' basketball trotter has spent more than 60 years of his life in connection with the land and, thanks to him, has traveled around the world.
Few people in Puerto Rico have a knowledge of the history of local basketball as large as that of Héctor "Hetin" Reyes.
The reason is that before a brain hemorrhage did not condemn him to the wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was immersed in this sport for more than 60 years, whether as a lower league player, a national basketball team player, the national team manager and leader, the BSN, with the Bayamón Vaqueros or as president of the basketball federation.
"I carried several helmets in basketball throughout my life, and even several at the same time, as when I was president of the National Team, Director General of the National Team and President of the Federation during the 1990s," Reyes recalls during a visit of First Hour to him in Bayamón, where he has been living with Isabel, his faithful wife for more than 50 years.
"Basket-ball is my whole life."
Reyes does not exaggerate when he makes that statement.
The walls of his house, almost all decorated with photos and souvenirs that remind him of his itinerary out of order, testify.
Bayamón in the heart
Of all his memories, the ones he loves most are those who remind him of his passage as a player in the Vacaros team in the mid-50s until 1982, after having spent 15 years as a co-manager or manager of the team.
"This has been my best years, the ones I've enjoyed most because I've had the chance to take part in eight cowboy championships since 1967, whether as manager, co-manager or leader.
This has been a lot of years of satisfaction, including the five championships held from 1971 to 1975.
Then I retired at the 1981 championship, the year that Jerome Mincy joined the BSN team.
From there, "Cuco" Ortiz, who was a great manager, took the lead of the team," says Reyes.
I remember that Gene Bartow, who had been the leader here and was at the University of Alabama (Birmingham), said to me: "I have a hard player for you, it measures two meters.
You want it?"
That's how to start Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico ever had.
Bartow then recommended me Raymond Gausse, who was naturalized and who was one of the best shooters.
I remember him saying that if Mincy had allowed Bayamon to win a championship, Gausse was going to help us try to win another one.
He welcomed the Vaqueros Championship with Gausse, but only at a distance since in 1988 he was already the great manitou of the federation.
At that time, he preferred to take advantage of Mincy's duties and those on the national team.
I remember when we first won it in the United States at the pre-olympic tournament in Mexico in 1989.
Then there was the 1990 World Cup, where we arrived 4th and where we should have won the bronze medal if this Canadian judge hadn't let us play the last game, Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup team the best national team you've ever seen?
She's one of the best, just like the one that beat the Dream Team at the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite is that of the Pan American Games in Cuba in 1991, when we won the gold and put a rattle on the U.S. team, which was quite similar to the one that won the bronze in the World Cup.
