This semester, when Professor of Religion Stuart Charmé decided to give a course on the end of the world, he knew that he was launching an irresistible hammock: the end of the "great count" of the Mayan calendar on 21 December, to which many people refer as proof of the end of the imminent world.
But Professor Charmé had no idea of what awaited him in the following months: the catastrophic hurricane Sandy, a tax wretch that some called "the Armageddon of debt" and a growing conflict involving Israel, the place where the Christian theorists of the end of time thought would trigger the apocalypse.
"I didn't realize that this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester I've ever known," said Professor Charmé this week to his students at Rutgers-Camden University (New Jersey).
