And it must be remembered that what is evil is good for those who believe in the apocalypse.
And he is not the only teacher to give courses on "the end of the world" this semester, which will, in theory, be the last of history.
In the Temple, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker delivered the course "Media, Culture and End of the World".
Every week, students explore apocalyptic themes such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and germs and climate warming.
"We analyze this because these ideas flourish over time," he said, and the way they provide hypothetical scenarios guides a certain human conduct.
If nuclear weapons were to fall into the hands of terrorists, for example, a war could break out.
This month, students will analyze films with apocalyptic themes and study how they can be compared with examples of real life.
"I tried to inform my students about what was possible, likely, credible and impossible," Vacker said.
